3574/* ===============================================================
3575 *
3576 * FONT
3577 *
3578 * ===============================================================*/
3579/* Font handling in this library was designed to be quite customizable and lets
3580 you decide what you want to use and what you want to provide. There are three
3581 different ways to use the font atlas. The first two will use your font
3582 handling scheme and only requires essential data to run nuklear. The next
3583 slightly more advanced features is font handling with vertex buffer output.
3584 Finally the most complex API wise is using nuklear's font baking API.
3585
3586 1.) Using your own implementation without vertex buffer output
3587 --------------------------------------------------------------
3588 So first up the easiest way to do font handling is by just providing a
3589 `nk_user_font` struct which only requires the height in pixel of the used
3590 font and a callback to calculate the width of a string. This way of handling
3591 fonts is best fitted for using the normal draw shape command API where you
3592 do all the text drawing yourself and the library does not require any kind
3593 of deeper knowledge about which font handling mechanism you use.
3594 IMPORTANT: the `nk_user_font` pointer provided to nuklear has to persist
3595 over the complete life time! I know this sucks but it is currently the only
3596 way to switch between fonts.
3597
3598 float your_text_width_calculation(nk_handle handle, float height, const char *text, int len)
3599 {
3600 your_font_type *type = handle.ptr;
3601 float text_width = ...;
3602 return text_width;
3603 }
3604
3605 struct nk_user_font font;
3606 font.userdata.ptr = &your_font_class_or_struct;
3607 font.height = your_font_height;
3608 font.width = your_text_width_calculation;
3609
3610 struct nk_context ctx;
3611 nk_init_default(&ctx, &font);
3612
3613 2.) Using your own implementation with vertex buffer output
3614 --------------------------------------------------------------
3615 While the first approach works fine if you don't want to use the optional
3616 vertex buffer output it is not enough if you do. To get font handling working
3617 for these cases you have to provide two additional parameters inside the
3618 `nk_user_font`. First a texture atlas handle used to draw text as subimages
3619 of a bigger font atlas texture and a callback to query a character's glyph
3620 information (offset, size, ...). So it is still possible to provide your own
3621 font and use the vertex buffer output.
3622
3623 float your_text_width_calculation(nk_handle handle, float height, const char *text, int len)
3624 {
3625 your_font_type *type = handle.ptr;
3626 float text_width = ...;
3627 return text_width;
3628 }
3629 void query_your_font_glyph(nk_handle handle, float font_height, struct nk_user_font_glyph *glyph, nk_rune codepoint, nk_rune next_codepoint)
3630 {
3631 your_font_type *type = handle.ptr;
3632 glyph.width = ...;
3633 glyph.height = ...;
3634 glyph.xadvance = ...;
3635 glyph.uv[0].x = ...;
3636 glyph.uv[0].y = ...;
3637 glyph.uv[1].x = ...;
3638 glyph.uv[1].y = ...;
3639 glyph.offset.x = ...;
3640 glyph.offset.y = ...;
3641 }
3642
3643 struct nk_user_font font;
3644 font.userdata.ptr = &your_font_class_or_struct;
3645 font.height = your_font_height;
3646 font.width = your_text_width_calculation;
3647 font.query = query_your_font_glyph;
3648 font.texture.id = your_font_texture;
3649
3650 struct nk_context ctx;
3651 nk_init_default(&ctx, &font);
3652
3653 3.) Nuklear font baker
3654 ------------------------------------
3655 The final approach if you do not have a font handling functionality or don't
3656 want to use it in this library is by using the optional font baker.
3657 The font baker APIs can be used to create a font plus font atlas texture
3658 and can be used with or without the vertex buffer output.
3659
3660 It still uses the `nk_user_font` struct and the two different approaches
3661 previously stated still work. The font baker is not located inside
3662 `nk_context` like all other systems since it can be understood as more of
3663 an extension to nuklear and does not really depend on any `nk_context` state.
3664
3665 Font baker need to be initialized first by one of the nk_font_atlas_init_xxx
3666 functions. If you don't care about memory just call the default version
3667 `nk_font_atlas_init_default` which will allocate all memory from the standard library.
3668 If you want to control memory allocation but you don't care if the allocated
3669 memory is temporary and therefore can be freed directly after the baking process
3670 is over or permanent you can call `nk_font_atlas_init`.
3671
3672 After successfully initializing the font baker you can add Truetype(.ttf) fonts from
3673 different sources like memory or from file by calling one of the `nk_font_atlas_add_xxx`.
3674 functions. Adding font will permanently store each font, font config and ttf memory block(!)
3675 inside the font atlas and allows to reuse the font atlas. If you don't want to reuse
3676 the font baker by for example adding additional fonts you can call
3677 `nk_font_atlas_cleanup` after the baking process is over (after calling nk_font_atlas_end).
3678
3679 As soon as you added all fonts you wanted you can now start the baking process
3680 for every selected glyph to image by calling `nk_font_atlas_bake`.
3681 The baking process returns image memory, width and height which can be used to
3682 either create your own image object or upload it to any graphics library.
3683 No matter which case you finally have to call `nk_font_atlas_end` which
3684 will free all temporary memory including the font atlas image so make sure
3685 you created our texture beforehand. `nk_font_atlas_end` requires a handle
3686 to your font texture or object and optionally fills a `struct nk_draw_null_texture`
3687 which can be used for the optional vertex output. If you don't want it just
3688 set the argument to `NULL`.
3689
3690 At this point you are done and if you don't want to reuse the font atlas you
3691 can call `nk_font_atlas_cleanup` to free all truetype blobs and configuration
3692 memory. Finally if you don't use the font atlas and any of it's fonts anymore
3693 you need to call `nk_font_atlas_clear` to free all memory still being used.
3694
3695 struct nk_font_atlas atlas;
3696 nk_font_atlas_init_default(&atlas);
3697 nk_font_atlas_begin(&atlas);
3698 nk_font *font = nk_font_atlas_add_from_file(&atlas, "Path/To/Your/TTF_Font.ttf", 13, 0);
3699 nk_font *font2 = nk_font_atlas_add_from_file(&atlas, "Path/To/Your/TTF_Font2.ttf", 16, 0);
3700 const void* img = nk_font_atlas_bake(&atlas, &img_width, &img_height, NK_FONT_ATLAS_RGBA32);
3701 nk_font_atlas_end(&atlas, nk_handle_id(texture), 0);
3702
3703 struct nk_context ctx;
3704 nk_init_default(&ctx, &font->handle);
3705 while (1) {
3706
3707 }
3708 nk_font_atlas_clear(&atlas);
3709
3710 The font baker API is probably the most complex API inside this library and
3711 I would suggest reading some of my examples `example/` to get a grip on how
3712 to use the font atlas. There are a number of details I left out. For example
3713 how to merge fonts, configure a font with `nk_font_config` to use other languages,
3714 use another texture coordinate format and a lot more:
3715
3716 struct nk_font_config cfg = nk_font_config(font_pixel_height);
3717 cfg.merge_mode = nk_false or nk_true;
3718 cfg.range = nk_font_korean_glyph_ranges();
3719 cfg.coord_type = NK_COORD_PIXEL;
3720 nk_font *font = nk_font_atlas_add_from_file(&atlas, "Path/To/Your/TTF_Font.ttf", 13, &cfg);
3721
3722*/

3887/* ==============================================================
3888 *
3889 * MEMORY BUFFER
3890 *
3891 * ===============================================================*/
3892/* A basic (double)-buffer with linear allocation and resetting as only
3893 freeing policy. The buffer's main purpose is to control all memory management
3894 inside the GUI toolkit and still leave memory control as much as possible in
3895 the hand of the user while also making sure the library is easy to use if
3896 not as much control is needed.
3897 In general all memory inside this library can be provided from the user in
3898 three different ways.
3899
3900 The first way and the one providing most control is by just passing a fixed
3901 size memory block. In this case all control lies in the hand of the user
3902 since he can exactly control where the memory comes from and how much memory
3903 the library should consume. Of course using the fixed size API removes the
3904 ability to automatically resize a buffer if not enough memory is provided so
3905 you have to take over the resizing. While being a fixed sized buffer sounds
3906 quite limiting, it is very effective in this library since the actual memory
3907 consumption is quite stable and has a fixed upper bound for a lot of cases.
3908
3909 If you don't want to think about how much memory the library should allocate
3910 at all time or have a very dynamic UI with unpredictable memory consumption
3911 habits but still want control over memory allocation you can use the dynamic
3912 allocator based API. The allocator consists of two callbacks for allocating
3913 and freeing memory and optional userdata so you can plugin your own allocator.
3914
3915 The final and easiest way can be used by defining
3916 NK_INCLUDE_DEFAULT_ALLOCATOR which uses the standard library memory
3917 allocation functions malloc and free and takes over complete control over
3918 memory in this library.
3919*/
3920struct nk_memory_status {
3921 void *memory;
3922 unsigned int type;
3923 nk_size size;
3924 nk_size allocated;
3925 nk_size needed;
3926 nk_size calls;
3927};
3928
3929enum nk_allocation_type {
3930 NK_BUFFER_FIXED,
3931 NK_BUFFER_DYNAMIC
3932};
3933
3934enum nk_buffer_allocation_type {
3935 NK_BUFFER_FRONT,
3936 NK_BUFFER_BACK,
3937 NK_BUFFER_MAX
3938};
3939
3940struct nk_buffer_marker {
3941 nk_bool active;
3942 nk_size offset;
3943};
3944
3945struct nk_memory {void *ptr;nk_size size;};
3946struct nk_buffer {
3947 struct nk_buffer_marker marker[NK_BUFFER_MAX];
3948 /* buffer marker to free a buffer to a certain offset */
3949 struct nk_allocator pool;
3950 /* allocator callback for dynamic buffers */
3951 enum nk_allocation_type type;
3952 /* memory management type */
3953 struct nk_memory memory;
3954 /* memory and size of the current memory block */
3955 float grow_factor;
3956 /* growing factor for dynamic memory management */
3957 nk_size allocated;
3958 /* total amount of memory allocated */
3959 nk_size needed;
3960 /* totally consumed memory given that enough memory is present */
3961 nk_size calls;
3962 /* number of allocation calls */
3963 nk_size size;
3964 /* current size of the buffer */
3965};

4038/*===============================================================
4039 *
4040 * TEXT EDITOR
4041 *
4042 * ===============================================================*/
4043/* Editing text in this library is handled by either `nk_edit_string` or
4044 * `nk_edit_buffer`. But like almost everything in this library there are multiple
4045 * ways of doing it and a balance between control and ease of use with memory
4046 * as well as functionality controlled by flags.
4047 *
4048 * This library generally allows three different levels of memory control:
4049 * First of is the most basic way of just providing a simple char array with
4050 * string length. This method is probably the easiest way of handling simple
4051 * user text input. Main upside is complete control over memory while the biggest
4052 * downside in comparison with the other two approaches is missing undo/redo.
4053 *
4054 * For UIs that require undo/redo the second way was created. It is based on
4055 * a fixed size nk_text_edit struct, which has an internal undo/redo stack.
4056 * This is mainly useful if you want something more like a text editor but don't want
4057 * to have a dynamically growing buffer.
4058 *
4059 * The final way is using a dynamically growing nk_text_edit struct, which
4060 * has both a default version if you don't care where memory comes from and an
4061 * allocator version if you do. While the text editor is quite powerful for its
4062 * complexity I would not recommend editing gigabytes of data with it.
4063 * It is rather designed for uses cases which make sense for a GUI library not for
4064 * an full blown text editor.
4065 */
4066#ifndef NK_TEXTEDIT_UNDOSTATECOUNT
4067#define NK_TEXTEDIT_UNDOSTATECOUNT 99
4068#endif
4069
4070#ifndef NK_TEXTEDIT_UNDOCHARCOUNT
4071#define NK_TEXTEDIT_UNDOCHARCOUNT 999
4072#endif

4153/* ===============================================================
4154 *
4155 * DRAWING
4156 *
4157 * ===============================================================*/
4158/* This library was designed to be render backend agnostic so it does
4159 not draw anything to screen. Instead all drawn shapes, widgets
4160 are made of, are buffered into memory and make up a command queue.
4161 Each frame therefore fills the command buffer with draw commands
4162 that then need to be executed by the user and his own render backend.
4163 After that the command buffer needs to be cleared and a new frame can be
4164 started. It is probably important to note that the command buffer is the main
4165 drawing API and the optional vertex buffer API only takes this format and
4166 converts it into a hardware accessible format.
4167
4168 To use the command queue to draw your own widgets you can access the
4169 command buffer of each window by calling `nk_window_get_canvas` after
4170 previously having called `nk_begin`:
4171
4172 void draw_red_rectangle_widget(struct nk_context *ctx)
4173 {
4174 struct nk_command_buffer *canvas;
4175 struct nk_input *input = &ctx->input;
4176 canvas = nk_window_get_canvas(ctx);
4177
4178 struct nk_rect space;
4179 enum nk_widget_layout_states state;
4180 state = nk_widget(&space, ctx);
4181 if (!state) return;
4182
4183 if (state != NK_WIDGET_ROM)
4184 update_your_widget_by_user_input(...);
4185 nk_fill_rect(canvas, space, 0, nk_rgb(255,0,0));
4186 }
4187
4188 if (nk_begin(...)) {
4189 nk_layout_row_dynamic(ctx, 25, 1);
4190 draw_red_rectangle_widget(ctx);
4191 }
4192 nk_end(..)
4193
4194 Important to know if you want to create your own widgets is the `nk_widget`
4195 call. It allocates space on the panel reserved for this widget to be used,
4196 but also returns the state of the widget space. If your widget is not seen and does
4197 not have to be updated it is '0' and you can just return. If it only has
4198 to be drawn the state will be `NK_WIDGET_ROM` otherwise you can do both
4199 update and draw your widget. The reason for separating is to only draw and
4200 update what is actually necessary which is crucial for performance.
4201*/
4202enum nk_command_type {
4203 NK_COMMAND_NOP,
4204 NK_COMMAND_SCISSOR,
4205 NK_COMMAND_LINE,
4206 NK_COMMAND_CURVE,
4207 NK_COMMAND_RECT,
4208 NK_COMMAND_RECT_FILLED,
4209 NK_COMMAND_RECT_MULTI_COLOR,
4210 NK_COMMAND_CIRCLE,
4211 NK_COMMAND_CIRCLE_FILLED,
4212 NK_COMMAND_ARC,
4213 NK_COMMAND_ARC_FILLED,
4214 NK_COMMAND_TRIANGLE,
4215 NK_COMMAND_TRIANGLE_FILLED,
4216 NK_COMMAND_POLYGON,
4217 NK_COMMAND_POLYGON_FILLED,
4218 NK_COMMAND_POLYLINE,
4219 NK_COMMAND_TEXT,
4220 NK_COMMAND_IMAGE,
4221 NK_COMMAND_CUSTOM
4222};

4485/* The optional vertex buffer draw list provides a 2D drawing context
4486 with antialiasing functionality which takes basic filled or outlined shapes
4487 or a path and outputs vertexes, elements and draw commands.
4488 The actual draw list API is not required to be used directly while using this
4489 library since converting the default library draw command output is done by
4490 just calling `nk_convert` but I decided to still make this library accessible
4491 since it can be useful.
4492
4493 The draw list is based on a path buffering and polygon and polyline
4494 rendering API which allows a lot of ways to draw 2D content to screen.
4495 In fact it is probably more powerful than needed but allows even more crazy
4496 things than this library provides by default.

5271/*==============================================================
5272 * STACK
5273 * =============================================================*/
5274/* The style modifier stack can be used to temporarily change a
5275 * property inside `nk_style`. For example if you want a special
5276 * red button you can temporarily push the old button color onto a stack
5277 * draw the button with a red color and then you just pop the old color
5278 * back from the stack:
5279 *
5280 * nk_style_push_style_item(ctx, &ctx->style.button.normal, nk_style_item_color(nk_rgb(255,0,0)));
5281 * nk_style_push_style_item(ctx, &ctx->style.button.hover, nk_style_item_color(nk_rgb(255,0,0)));
5282 * nk_style_push_style_item(ctx, &ctx->style.button.active, nk_style_item_color(nk_rgb(255,0,0)));
5283 * nk_style_push_vec2(ctx, &cx->style.button.padding, nk_vec2(2,2));
5284 *
5285 * nk_button(...);
5286 *
5287 * nk_style_pop_style_item(ctx);
